</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaielmankajiraliege.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aielman KajiraLiege</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/23/02 7:09:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=594>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fallenalliance.org/screenshots/downwpst.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The State of Warriors in EQ</span><hr size=1> I'm entering into this discussion quite late in the thread, so forgive me if I go over some things that have been covered or answer things 25 pages back, but there are several things I'd like to say.<br>
<br>
Back on page 10 or so someone mentioned something about how could a headband have 40 ac and how could a warrior in full plate be expected to be dodging. Couple of things about plate and ac. First of all, it's a common misconception that plate is heavy...it really isn't. Chain is actually much heavier than plate (having worn armor before at SEA events/Ren Fests, I can attest to this personally). Plate is actually much lighter than chain and in many cases leather armor and the padding that go with it, and has been since the advent of the blast furnace in the 1200's. It just looks heavy, so Hollywood has always portrayed it as such and now everyone expects that it is. Second of all, there is a misconception about AC. Most of this game is loosely based off of the original D&amp;D/Dragonlance concepts for classes and gear. AC isn't just something that causes a character to be missed outright. It is also the armor turning blows, and thus what ac &quot;does&quot; takes to forms...it's sort of a catch all to explain many of the details of how damage is avoided in combat, without having to make 20 different skill checks. For the monk, the mystical headband makes somehow easier for them to do the Jackie Chan thing and use the best defense of No Be There. For the plate classes, it's the ability of the armor to turn a blow, ala most of the fighting in the movie Excalibur.<br>
<br>
That being said, I have a different perspective than alot of the views that have been posted by alot of the warriors here. Most of the discussion and counterpoints have been talking about end game and very high level equipment. I'm currently lvl 59 and probably will remain so for a very long time. I'm in a fairly large guild with about 150 members, but one with very limited raiding capabilities due to many factors...we just took down Vindi for the first time and are pretty pleased with ourselves and although we haven't takend down Doz yet, we do own the rest of HoT and have done rhag1 and 2 etc. Our guild is filled with people who are there as a group of friends who happen to raid from time to time, so alot of this discussion about &quot;Would you want a second warrior for a raid...&quot; etc doesn't apply to us because we'll take the second warrior and anyone else who wants to come along because we're friends and we're here to have fun. This isn't a knock on raiding guilds, we just aren't one. I will never be in a raiding guild no matter how bad ass i get or want to be because I can't make the commitment to raid that is usually the price of admission. If I want to take on the big boys, I just join another raid and contend with the likelihood that I will not ever get the prime loot, and just enjoy the fun of the takedown, which I do from time to time.<br>
<br>
Which brings me to my main point. I have, like many here, watched the steady errosion of my utility since Kunark came out (yes, I've been playing since the pre kunark days and still am not level 60). All of the points made here with regard to endgame warriors are very valid and concern me just as much as it does those that posted them. However, the majority of the players on just about every server are Not in one of the uber raiding guilds and probably never will be. Therefore, the assertions that there are &quot;taunt weapons&quot; in the game for warriors are pointless, as you are never going to see one of these weapons ever. My guild will likley Never even Attempt the AoW or Creator and will never see the inside of Vex Thal, and that's fine with us. But why should I, or the other warriors in my guild, or those in other smaller, non raid oriented guilds, have to contend with the mediocrity and in many cases, outright uselessness that our class has been relegated to over the last year, just because we can't get the top end gear. If we have to have an enraging blow weapon just to maintain taunt on HoT yard trash and Vex Thal gear just to be able to do our single focus job, then there is a fundamental flaw with the warrior character class<br>
<br>
There has been much discussion here, and on other boards, about warrior dps vs pally/sk with the knights saying we have more and the warriors saying that isn't necessarily true. I say it's completely true if you aren't in the end game, don't have 25AA pts, and/or aren't in a high end raiding guild. I currently use an Ornate sword of the General and a CBoL as my only weapons. I use these piddly damage weapons because the Only agro i can generate is from hitting the mob as rapidly as possible, and they are the best I've been able to get.  I parse our raid encounters as do others in our guild and find, time and time again, that the paladins and sk's of our guild, even those as low as lvl 54, equal or better my damage every time unless I'm the MT and hitting the mob before anyone else. Because of agro issues, I usually tank for up to a full minute before the assist is called to insure I'm far enough up on the hate list to maintain some agro. It's a 50/50 shot that, even after a minute, a ranger or monk with epics inadvertantly taunts off a mob or some dress wearer gets a free trip to bind point just for doing a normal nuke. <br>
<br>
My panoply is mixed champion/cobalt/SS armor with IGS, CoCW and other easily obtainable items...I have 6k in the bank, which is 4kk shy of the most I've ever seen at one time and for me, the biggest upgrade i'm likely to see for the forseeable future is full SS armor. I am at 4800 hp with about 1300ac fully raid buffed by our level 60 buffers. Pitiful, I know, but that's where I am...and that's where alot of other warriors are as well. The upgrades to the knight classes have given them not just near parity to people like me, but in many cases, superiority. <br>
<br>
I don't begrude the knights a damn bit the improvements they've been given...they were pitiful when Kunark first came out. I don't want to see anything taken away from them...in fact I am in agreement that they need what is coming from the new shield upgrade, even though it will cause me to quit the game if there aren't vast improvements made to warriors at the same time that this comes out. I'll but completely useless unless i want to get a shield myself and cut my pitiful damage output down by 1/3 to 1/2 what it is now. Then ill only be partially useless.<br>
<br>
The fact still remains that Warriors are a single focus class. We are THE melee class. All other classes are specialists in one aspect of melee or generalists that dabble in magic. By the very nature of our class, we have given up any rapid movement, healing, buffing and everything else in the pursuit of pure martial ability. We should be able to take twice the damage of any other class...not avoid it, but absorb it. We should Not be the greatests damage dealers by any stretch of the imagination, but it should be damn tough to make us go away. In my opinion, knights Should do more damage than warriors in any situation with the undead or those in diametric opposition to thier god, as they are supposed to be mortal avatars of thier god. They should never do more damage (equally equipped) on any other types of mobs as they are still mortal men using the same blades warriors are. Monks have trainging in mystical arts that should allow them to know how to deal maximum damage with the open hand ( i personally think they should do as much or more damage barehanded than with a weapon), but they should drop quicker than my ex wife at fleet week if they fail to avoid being hit. Monks don't absorb damage...they avoid it...remember...&quot;best defense, noooo be there&quot;. Where the warrior should shine is in his ability to shake it off. At no time should anyone even consider having any other class stand before the badguy and take the blows. There has to be a trade-off or you might as well get rid of the warrior class. <br>
<br>
To those knights out there that feel &quot;it's about time&quot; or &quot;We should tank every bit as well as warriors&quot; you are wrong. You have to pay to play...if you want the blessing of your god which allows you to heal or do other spells and kick the living crap out of the undead (hell, i say make them even more effective than they are now in this regard), then the trade-off has to be made. In standard rpg's the trade-off is that you could not anger your god or you would lose your powers. That would mean, in this game, that if you attacked enough creatures on the same faction as your god, you'd cease to be a paladin but would become a warrior, but half as effective in all areas because you weren't as martially trained. If you, as a knight, want to tank as well as a warrior and want to have parity in hp/dps/ac then that's the trade-off you should have to face. That isn't an option here...the god's aren't PC's with the capricious whims they would have in a normal rpg. So you have to make another trade-off...you can NOT be as effective of a tank without completely marginalizing the warriors. If you want to tank, be a warrior. If you want to use melee and spells, then deal with being much less effective at absorbing damage and keeping the interest of the mob. <br>
<br>
There should be only one instance where a knight is a good choice to be the tank in my opinion, and this is gonna piss off alot of warriors, but it's still my opinion. Knights are holy/unoly warriors...they should be equally if not marginally better main tanks against the undead. They should have a defense table just for the undead that gives them the same damage absorption capabilities a warrior has for every mob. They should also always be able to easily out taunt a warrior when facing the undead or followers of a god at war with theirs. This would make the game much more true to the intended natures of each class and would make a raid need both warriors and knights to be raid capable everywhere. Knights could be the badass in some zones and warriors in others when it came to xp grind and as most boss mobs are not undead, the utility of a knight would still make them sought after for high end encounters.<br>
<br>
It's our one and only thing and it needs to be restored. It needs to be done quickly and without being at the expense of the gains that have already been made by the hybrid classes.<br>
<br>
Sorry to be so long winded, but I had alot I wanted to say after reading so many posts.<br>
<br>
peace,<br>
Aielman KajiraLiege<br>
Birds of Prey, Prexus Server <p><center><img src="http://members.aol.com/azarielleeq/images/aieldon.jpg">
